frigeration system (i.e., the use of anhydrous ammonia) is a 24-hour per day, 365-day per year operation that is cold storage and refrigeration at the Stockton Distribution Center.  



The anhydrous ammonia storage, handling, and use system at the Stockton Warehouse and Distribution Center consists of the following main components:

?    Two high temperature screw compressors;

?    Two low temperature screw compressors;

?    Two evaporative condensers;

?    The main high-pressure receiver;

?    The high temperature recirculator package;

?    The low temperature recirculator package;

?    Four ammonia pumps; and

?    Seventeen evaporators.



Additional system components include:

?    Oil Pots (one each at each liquid recirculator package for draining oil);

?    Automatic Purger (with a foul gas tap at the evaporative condensers and a tap on the high pressure liquid line from the high pressure receiver and the liquid recirculation packages);

?    One (1) Floor-Warming Heat Exchanger using glycol as the heat transfer fluid; and,

?    Interconnecting Piping and Control Valves. 



Safety systems include:

?    Pressure relief valves on all pressure vessels in the system;

?    An ammonia diffusion tank, 15,600 gallon capacity (all relief valve discharge lines lead to the diffusion tank for mixing with water in the event of a release from a component relief valve); 

?    Fire dump valve arrangement in ammonia diffusion panel for use by the fire department in the event of an emergency; 

?    Compressor safety cutouts and control panels to shut down the compressor operation if safe operating conditions are exceeded; 

?    Liquid level float switches; 

?    High level vessel alarms; 

?    Dual hot-gas solenoid valves;

?    PLC alarm notification; 

?    Ventilation system for continuous and emergency ventilation;

?    Emergency Control Station with emergency ventilation fan switch and emergency shutdown switch;

?    Ammonia detection and alarm system for response to elevated levels of ammonia vapor in the cooling, freeze

r, and storage areas (detection of ammonia triggers the emergency ventilation system, emergency shutdown, and audible/visual alarms at preset levels);

?    Spring-loaded, self-closing oil drain valves;

?    Manual stop valves; 

?    Manual and solenoid-controlled King Valve to stop liquid refrigerant flow from the high pressure receiver; 

?    Physical barriers to protect equipment/piping from collisions (e.g. bollards); 

?    Fire sprinkler system; 

?    Portable fire extinguishers; and

?    Emergency showers and eyewash stations.



The extent of involvement in the operation of the refrigeration system by employees is limited to daily monitoring and recording. The maintenance of the system is contracted to a qualified refrigeration contractor. 



Water Based Anhydrous Ammonia Diffusion System

ALL system pressure relief valves are piped to a main header and into an above-ground water storage tank (with approximate volume of 15,600-gallons of water).  All pressure relief valves are piped to the diffusion tank for mixing with water in the event of a release from one of the system's pressure relief valves.  The water in the diffusion tank provides scrubbing of the anhydrous ammonia vapor prior to discharge to the atmosphere.  This virtually eliminates offsite impacts from potential pressure relief events.



Site Security

A chain link fence surrounds the facility.  Additionally, the facility is protected via manned 24-hour security.  These site security provisions are intended to prevent unauthorized access to facility areas.  Lastly, the refrigeration machinery room is locked at all times and can only be accessed by authorized personnel. 



